recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Bird foraging very actively, almost frenetic, in privet and lower branches of trees along the entrance path ~3-5m above the ground.

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Guerneville, Sonoma County, California
recordings.rmk:
Hi there, I got a pretty poor look at a very young fledgling (through a lot of bramble) that I believe was making the high pitched calls heard at the beginning of this recording. There were a couple Wilson's Warblers active in the same area and I did see one fly over to the general bramble area where the fledgling was sitting. Unfortunately, I didn't actually see them interact and I am unsure if I actually saw a very young WIWA or a different bird. The bird was pretty plain gray, with big black eyes and a large mouth gape. 

Does anybody know if these vocalizations are from a begging Wilson's Warbler fledgling? I could only find one recording of a fledgling WIWA in the database by Ian Cruickshank and I was unsure which vocalization he was referring to as the fledgling calls.

Any help is appreciated. Thanks!

Highpass filter @ 12khz
Redwood/Doug-fir forest

Miles

recordings.loc: Orick, Humboldt County, California
recordings.rmk:
This 90 second recording exhibits a single adult male Wilson’s Warbler in song. He sings 9 times. Nearby there was a juvie Chestnut-backed Chickadee begging while following an adult around.

More details of the context of this recording may be found here: <http://ebird.org/ebird/view/checklist?subID=S30431123>

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with built-in mic. This is an unedited and unmodified recording of the natural spacing of these birds' utterances.
